@flexiarg t3/adaptive-delivery-spine
@title Protected Interaction
@sigils [🪡/式]
@audience trainers, curriculum-designers, cohort-leads
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/intervention-triad
@see t3/expectation-scaffold, t3/living-materials-stewardship
@next t3/living-materials-stewardship
@tier intervention
@confidence high
@npt-domain 3.3 Skill Set Workability, 3.4 Contextual Integration
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Interaction time is protected when the delivery structure absorbs local variation. Where sessions try to cover everything uniformly, interaction shrinks, core concepts get diluted, and trainers feel unprepared to deliver outside their expertise.

  + context: T3 sessions cover a broad range of open research topics; trainers have diverse disciplinary backgrounds and cannot realistically deliver all content with equal confidence.
  + if: You want trainers to tailor content to local needs without losing coherence or confidence.
  + however: One-size-fits-all agendas create fatigue, reduce interaction, and leave trainers unable to cover core material; impostor syndrome compounds the problem for professional staff delivering outside their expertise.
  + then: Define a delivery spine: a minimal core (two to three modules) plus named elective modules and a required co-working block for local adaptation. Provide time budgets and "drop-in" variants for short sessions.
  + because: A spine creates predictable structure while legitimising adaptation; it protects interaction time and reduces overload; trainers who focus on what they know deliver more confidently.
      + mechanism: A fixed core preserves coherence while electives absorb local variance, keeping interaction time intact and reducing the breadth-versus-depth tension.
      + counterfactual: If we deliver the full deck uniformly, interaction time shrinks, core concepts get diluted, and trainers feel unprepared.
      + applies-when: Sessions vary in length and audience, and trainers need guidance on what to trim or expand.
      + does-not-apply: A pilot with a single, fixed module and no need for local tailoring.
      + signals: Trainers regularly overrun, report dropping content ad hoc, or describe impostor syndrome about breadth.
      + evidence: "My top tips are to either give it more time than you expect" (T1); "I didn't feel prepared to talk about all the areas" (T2A); "There's a little bit of impostor syndrome, because it's still new to me and no one's taught me it!" (T3); "Probably 80% of the stuff I learned... I don't then replicate" (T2B). COM-B: "I am psychologically able" M=4.85.
  + next-steps:
      - Publish three spine variants (90-min, half-day, full-day).
      - Add a template for local adaptation notes and decisions.
      - Include a standard Q&A and co-working segment in every variant.
  + governance:
      - practice: collect post-session notes on what was dropped or adapted.
      - metric: percentage of sessions using a declared spine variant.
